### What to expect (concise, numeric):

* **Time**: Potential precompute drops from (n^2) to (nK). For (n=200, K=16), that’s **~12.5× fewer** potential updates per restart. Removing int64 distance matrix and integer sqrt cuts distance setup time roughly in half or better.
* **Quality**: Slightly larger K (10→16) plus the k-opt actually exploring (exploration coefficient 0.15) improves acceptance of profitable chains. With BHH ≈ 10.07, expect your median 200-city tours to move from ~**10.9–11.2** toward **10.5–10.8**, often faster due to early-stall exit.
* **Stability**: Using `exp()` reduces FP cost; disabling heat map avoids useless I/O/allocs (your HM was zeros).

If you want one more quick win later: **symmetric candidate augmentation** (ensure if (j\in N(i)) then (i\in N(j))) often gives a free bump to 2-opt efficacy without raising K materially.
